excerpt:
Recently, I encountered a weird bug that when calling to getAnalysis&lt;...&gt; from
an LLVM function pass, my program crashes!

Debugging a crash bug has never been considered easy in C++! Here is the
problematic code:

bool MyFuncPass::runOnFunction(Function &amp;F) {
  DominatorTree &amp;DT = getAnalysis&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;(F).getDomTree();
  ...
  return true;
}


It had baffled me for several weeks, since I did declare the usage of the
DominatorTreeWrapperPass in the function getAnalysisUsage.

struct MyFuncPass : public FunctionPass {
  static char ID;
  MyFuncPass() : FunctionPass(ID) {}

  void getAnalysisUsage(AnalysisUsage &amp;AU) const override {
    AU.addRequired&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;();
  }

  virtual bool runOnFunction(Function &amp;F) override;
};


Moreover, when turning this function pass into a module pass, everything is
fine!

struct MyModuPass : public ModulePass {
  static char ID;
  MyModuPass() : ModulePass(ID) {}

  void getAnalysisUsage(AnalysisUsage &amp;AU) const override {
    AU.addRequired&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;();
  }

  virtual bool runOnModule(Function &amp;F) override;
};

bool MyModuPass::runOnModule(Module &amp;M) {
  for (Function &amp;F: M) {
    // using the same call as in MyFuncPass::runOnFunction
    // but here, it works, suprisingly!
    DominatorTree &amp;DT = getAnalysis&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;(F).getDomTree();
  }

  return true;
}


After spending quite a lot of effort on googling, StackOverflow, reading LLVM
mailing list and source code, finally, I realized the problem is that
I did not call getAnalysis correctly in the function pass.

In particular:



    For a module pass, to obtain the dominator tree of a function F, you can call:

    // call inside a module pass
DominatorTree &amp;DT = getAnalysis&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;(F).getDomTree();



    But, for a function pass, you should not pass the function F as an
argument for getAnalysis (if you do, your program will crash!). So, the
following code is enough:

    // call inside a function pass
DominatorTree &amp;DT = getAnalysis&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;().getDomTree();




So, the final code for a function pass that works for me is something like below:

struct MyFuncPass : public FunctionPass {
  static char ID;
  MyFuncPass() : FunctionPass(ID) {}

  void getAnalysisUsage(AnalysisUsage &amp;AU) const override {
    AU.addRequired&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;();
  }

  virtual bool runOnFunction(Function &amp;F) override;
};

bool MyFuncPass::runOnFunction(Function &amp;F) {
  // Remember to NOT pass F to getAnalysis. No crash with this code!
  DominatorTree &amp;DT = getAnalysis&lt;DominatorTreeWrapperPass&gt;().getDomTree();
  ...
  return true;
}


Magical!!! Right?

It took me a few weeks to finally realize it!

